"""
era_melchizedek_origins.py -- Melchizedek Origins (Chapters 1-3)

Genesis 14 introduces the most enigmatic figure in the Hebrew Bible: a king-priest
who appears without genealogy, blesses Abraham, receives tithes, and vanishes from
the narrative. Melchizedek (malki-tsedeq, 'my king is righteousness') rules Salem
(shalem, 'peace/wholeness') and serves as priest of El Elyon -- the Most High God.
His appearance predates Israel, Levi, Aaron, and the entire Mosaic system by centuries.
The author of Hebrews will argue that this silence about Melchizedek's origins is
itself the point: a priesthood that does not depend on bloodline, tribe, or succession.

The Levitical priesthood, by contrast, was hedged with requirements: Aaronic descent,
tribal membership in Levi, physical qualifications, ordination rituals, and -- most
critically -- mortality. Every Levitical priest eventually died and had to be replaced.
Hebrews 7:23-24 drives the nail: 'The former priests were many in number, because
they were prevented by death from continuing in office, but he holds his priesthood
permanently, because he continues forever.' The Melchizedekian order solves the
problem the Levitical order could never fix.
"""

